  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several key ways:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- Establish common standards and expectations for anti-money laundering (AML) efforts\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries cooperate in investigations\n- Sharing of financial intelligence\n- Extradition of suspects\n- Seizure and forfeiture of illicit funds\n\n3. Standardized Reporting Requirements\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Uniform financial disclosure standards\n- Cross-border information exchange\n\n4. Compliance Mechanisms\n- Countries implement international standards domestically\n- National legislation aligned with global frameworks\n- Periodic evaluations of AML/CFT effectiveness\n- Potential sanctions for non-compliance\n\n5. Financial Institution Regulations\n- International banking standards\n- Uniform risk assessment protocols\n- Enhanced due diligence requirements\n- Cross-border transaction monitoring\n\n6. Technological Collaboration\n- Information sharing platforms\n- Coordinated cyber investigations\n- Tracking cryptocurrency transactions\n- Developing consistent digital forensic approaches\n\nThese intersections create a complex, multilayered approach to combating money laundering globally.",
